Not sure whether it helps those searching a solution, but for me the problem was a capabilities configuration where I used

```lua
capabilities.workspace = {
  didChangeWatchedFiles = {
    dynamicRegistration = true,
  },
}
```

After removing this from my `capabilities` table, it worked fine again.

I started hitting this issue today with `svelte-language-server` version 0.16.12 on macOS so I did some digging. In my current SvelteKit project, the LS is sending `client/registerCapability` with `workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles` with an array of watchers:

```lua
{
  id = 1,
  jsonrpc = "2.0",
  method = "client/registerCapability",
  params = {
    registrations = { {
        id = "8e52a737-4ad1-40eb-87bb-bfb06f587686",
        method = "workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles",
        registerOptions = {
          watchers = { {
              globPattern = {
                baseUri = "file:///Users/bryan/Projects/my-sveltekit-project/.svelte-kit/types",
                pattern = "**/*.{ts,js,mts,mjs,cjs,cts,json,svelte}"
              }
            }, {
              globPattern = {
                baseUri = "file:///Users/bryan/Projects/my-sveltekit-project/src",
                pattern = "**/*.{ts,js,mts,mjs,cjs,cts,json,svelte}"
              }
            }, {
              globPattern = {
                baseUri = "file:///Users/bryan/Projects/my-sveltekit-project/tests",
                pattern = "**/*.{ts,js,mts,mjs,cjs,cts,json,svelte}"
              }
            } }
        }
      } }
  }
}
```

This causes `M.register()` in `runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_watchfiles.lua` to run:

https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/v0.10.0/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_watchfiles.lua#L133-L152

When the loop gets to the third watcher object, it errors out because the `tests` directory does not exist (this is where the `ENOENT` error happens). It seems to me that either `M.watch()` in `runtime/lua/vim/_watch.lua` or `M.register()` should check if the directory exists before trying to create the watcher. I tried it out locally by changing lines 133-152 in `_watchfiles.lua` to the following:

```lua
  for base_dir, watches in pairs(watch_regs) do
    if vim.fn.isdirectory(base_dir) == 1 then
      local include_pattern = vim.iter(watches):fold(lpeg.P(false), function(acc, w)
        return acc + w.pattern
      end)

      table.insert(
        cancels[client_id][reg.id],
        M._watchfunc(base_dir, {
          uvflags = {
            recursive = true,
          },
          -- include_pattern will ensure the pattern from *any* watcher definition for the
          -- base_dir matches. This first pass prevents polling for changes to files that
          -- will never be sent to the LSP server. A second pass in the callback is still necessary to
          -- match a *particular* pattern+kind pair.
          include_pattern = include_pattern,
          exclude_pattern = M._poll_exclude_pattern,
        }, callback(base_dir))
      )
    end
  end
```
